<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix lemmonii </i>is a riparian shrub up to 5 m tall. Its leaves are bicolored and relatively hairless on top. Young leaves may be densely hairy but become glabrous to sparsely short-haired below when mature. Plants reproduce primarily through the dispersal of thousands of small seeds, which are dispersed by wind and water. Seeds remain viable for a few days and germinate on moist surfaces (Uchytil 1989h). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs in the mid-montane to high Sierra Nevada and Cascades along steep, rocky streamsides. According to Potter (2005), these upper-elevation meadow willow thickets characteristically receive water by subsurface and overland flows from upstream or upslope sources on a seasonal basis, and, although some sites are permanently saturated, most go dry in the surface during summer <i>. Carex </i>spp. collectively is the most constant (85%) and represents the highest cover (30%) of the herbaceous layers. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
