    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Salix lemmonii</i> includes the eastern Klamath Mountains (M261A), Modoc Plateau (M261G), Southern Cascades (M261D), San Bernardino Mountains (M262Bg), and White Mountains (341Dj).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf, Gi). S. Smith (1998b) described several preliminary types of this alliance that we list as mesic associations. Hickson et al. (2007) sampled stands in the Fitzhugh and Pine creek drainages. Surrounding upland stands typically include those of the <i>Juniperus occidentalis</i> and <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea, Ec-d, Eh, Ej-m, Eo, Eq, Et-u). Most inventories of this alliance are from the central and southern subsections (Potter 2005) and the east side (Manning and Padgett 1995). Manning and Padgett described several informal types that we list as mesic graminoid and tall forb associations, and Weixelman et al. (1999) cited a Cold willow/mesic graminoid type that relates directly to these types. Associated riparian shrublands are those of the <i>Alnus incana, Salix eastwoodiae, S. geyeriana, S. orestera,</i> and <i>Vaccinium uliginosum</i> alliances. Adjacent uplands stands are those of the <i>Abies concolor, Artemisia tridentata</i> ssp. <i>vaseyana, Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana, P. jeffreyi,</i> and <i>Populus tremuloides</i> alliances.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Studies (Green et al. 2003, C. Stermer pers. comm. 2005) suggest that <i>Salix lemmonii </i>stands provide habitat for willow flycatcher (Empidonax traillii), a threatened species in the Sierra Nevada. The dense nature of many stands provides hiding and foraging habitat for avian species and reduces stream temperatures for amphibians and native trout (Potter 2005). </div>
</div>

    

    

